# ArUco Mission System — Architecture Specification

**Audience:** Implementation AI agent
**Status:** Design only — no implementation code included
**Scope:** Replace all ArUco-driven decision logic above the detection layer with a configurable, extensible Mission System.

---

# Executive Summary

The project currently detects ArUco markers correctly but does almost nothing useful with them: `ArUcoHandler` hardcodes a 4-entry `id_map` to a fixed enum of events, `Navigator` only ever executes `LANE_FOLLOWING`, and every other state is an unused placeholder. Adding a new marker behaviour today means editing `if/elif` chains in at least two files and adding new enum members — this does not scale to "dozens or hundreds of markers," and it cannot express the first requested mission (random branch-or-continue at an intersection) at all.

This document specifies a replacement **Mission System** that sits between the existing low-level `ArUcoDetector` (kept as-is) and the existing low-level actuation layer (`AIDriver`, `MotorController`, kept as-is). It introduces:

- A **declarative Marker Registry** that maps marker ID → Mission Definition, with zero conditional logic in code.
- A **Mission Manager** that owns exactly one active mission at a time, arbitrates priority, tracks cooldowns/one-time markers, and guarantees the vehicle always has a well-defined behaviour.
- A **plugin-style Mission/Action framework**: every navigation behaviour (turn, stop, park, enter charging station, ignore, custom…) is an independent class implementing a common lifecycle interface. New behaviours are added by writing a new class and one registry entry — never by touching existing code.
- A **generic mission execution state machine** (`PENDING → APPROACH → PREPARE → EXECUTE → RECOVER → COMPLETE`) that every mission type reuses, so trajectory logic is not duplicated per marker.
- A **Random Route Selection** mechanism scoped to the mission instance (not global state), decided exactly once, resilient to marker flicker and camera dropout.
- A cross-cutting **Safety Monitor** that always outranks any active mission and can force an abort or emergency stop.

The only existing component this design preserves is `ArUcoDetector` (`ArUco/aruco_detector.py`), because it is technically sound: it correctly wraps `cv2.aruco`, performs `solvePnP` pose estimation, and returns per-marker id/corners/rvec/tvec/distance. `ArUcoHandler`, `Navigator`, `NavState`, and `ArUcoEvent` are all treated as prototype code to be fully replaced.

---

# Current Architecture Review

For context only — this is what exists today, and none of it constrains the new design beyond the detection layer.

| Component | File | Role today | Verdict |
|---|---|---|---|
| `ArUcoDetector` | `ArUco/aruco_detector.py` | Detects markers, estimates pose via `solvePnP`, returns `{id, corners, rvec, tvec, distance}` per marker | **Keep.** Clean, single-responsibility, hardware/library-correct. |
| `ArUcoHandler` | `autonomous_navigation/aruco_handler.py` | Hardcoded `id_map` (4 entries) → `ArUcoEvent` enum; fires the *first* marker under a single global `trigger_distance` | **Replace.** Not configurable, no priority, no cooldown, no per-marker parameters. |
| `ArUcoEvent` | same file | Flat string-constant enum (`STOP`, `ENTRY_DIAGONAL`, …) | **Replace.** Not extensible without editing the enum and every consumer. |
| `Navigator` | `autonomous_navigation/navigator.py` | State machine with 10 declared `NavState` values, of which only `IDLE`, `LANE_FOLLOWING`, `PAUSED` are reachable; all maneuver states are commented `# Reserved placeholder` | **Replace.** The skeleton names are a reasonable *inspiration* but the execution logic (`_start_maneuver`, yaw-delta turning) is unused, untested, and marker-specific by construction. |
| `RedLineDetector` | `autonomous_navigation/vision_events.py` | HSV-based red-line detector on lower ROI, returned to `Navigator.update()` but never consumed | **Keep as an optional Perception input**, not part of the Mission System itself. |
| `AIDriver` | `autonomous_navigation/ai_driver.py` | Wraps TFLite model, returns smoothed steering only | **Keep unchanged.** Mission System calls it during lane-following and during blended recovery, never modifies it. |
| `NavConfig` / `ArUcoConfig` | `config.py` | Scattered timers (`STOP_DURATION`, `PRE_TURN_ADVANCE`, `MANEUVER_STRAIGHT`, …) intended for the unused maneuver states | **Superseded** by the new per-marker declarative config (see §9), but the *values* are useful defaults to migrate. |
| `main_auto.py` | orchestration loop | Captures frame → `red_line_detector.detect()` → `navigator.update()` → `motors.move()` → HUD draw | **Integration point.** The new system plugs into this loop with the same call shape: one `update(frame, vehicle_state) -> (state_name, throttle, steering, debug_info)` call per frame. |

**What's available after detection today**, confirmed from `ArUcoDetector.detect()`: marker `id`, four corner points in image space, `rvec`/`tvec` (full 6-DOF pose relative to camera), and scalar Euclidean `distance`. This is sufficient to derive distance-to-marker and, via `tvec`'s x/y components, **lateral offset** and approach angle — both needed for the mission triggers requested (trigger distance, trigger direction). No additional sensor or perception capability is required for the first mission.

---

# Proposed Architecture

## 1. High-Level Architecture

```
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                         PERCEPTION LAYER                              |
|  Camera -> ArUcoDetector (unchanged) -> MarkerTracker                 |
|  Camera -> AIDriver (unchanged, lane steering)                        |
|  Camera -> RedLineDetector (unchanged, optional signal)                |
+---------------------------------+---------------------------------------+
                                  | MarkerSighting[], lane_steering, vehicle_state
                                  v
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                        MISSION SUBSYSTEM                               |
|                                                                          |
|   MarkerRegistry  --lookup-->  MissionDefinition (declarative)         |
|         |                              |                                |
|         v                              v                                |
|   MissionManager  <----------  MissionFactory (plugin registry)        |
|    - active mission                    |                                |
|    - pending candidates                v                                |
|    - cooldown ledger            Mission instance                       |
|    - completion history         (Approach/Prepare/Execute/Recover)      |
|         |                              |                                |
|         v                              v                                |
|   SafetyMonitor (cross-cutting, highest priority, every frame)          |
+---------------------------------+---------------------------------------+
                                  | (throttle, steering, nav_state, debug)
                                  v
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
|                          ACTUATION LAYER                                |
|           MotorController.move(throttle, steering) (unchanged)          |
|           TelemetryHUD.draw(...) (extended, not replaced)               |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
```

### Module responsibilities

- **`MarkerTracker`** (new, Perception Layer): Consumes raw per-frame `ArUcoDetector.detect()` output. Produces temporally-stable `MarkerSighting` objects: debounces flicker (requires N consecutive detections to confirm a "seen" event, M consecutive misses to confirm "lost"), converts `tvec` into `(distance, lateral_offset, bearing_angle)`, and tags each sighting with a monotonic timestamp and a stable `track_id` so the same physical marker isn't re-detected as a new event every frame. This is the component that makes the system "survive temporary marker loss," not the Mission Manager.

- **`MarkerRegistry`** (new): A pure data lookup — `marker_id -> MissionDefinition`. No behaviour, no branching. Backed by the configuration described in §9.

- **`MissionDefinition`** (new, data class): The declarative contract described in §3.

- **`MissionFactory`** (new): Maps `MissionDefinition.mission_type` (a string) → a concrete `Mission` subclass constructor. This is the plugin seam: adding a new mission type is "register a class," never "edit a dispatcher."

- **`Mission`** (new, abstract base class): Defines the lifecycle interface every mission type implements (§4, §6). Concrete examples: `ContinueStraightMission`, `IntersectionBranchMission`, `StopMission`, `SlowDownMission`, `IgnoreMission`, `ParkMission` (future), etc.

- **`MissionManager`** (new): Owns the single source of truth for "what is the vehicle currently doing at the mission level." Responsible for candidate validation, priority arbitration, cooldown/one-time enforcement, interruption, and cancellation (§2).

- **`SafetyMonitor`** (new, cross-cutting): Evaluated every frame regardless of mission state. Can veto mission activation, force abort, or force emergency stop. Always has final authority (§8).

- **`Navigator`** (replaces the current `Navigator` class, same name/role for integration simplicity, entirely new internals): The top-level per-frame `update()` entry point called by `main_auto.py`. Delegates lane-following to `AIDriver`, delegates everything mission-related to `MissionManager`, applies `SafetyMonitor` verdicts, and returns `(state_name, throttle, steering, debug_info)` — preserving the existing call contract used by `main_auto.py` and `TelemetryHUD`.

### Communication contract between modules

All cross-module communication uses small, immutable data objects (not dictionaries with implicit keys), passed by value each frame:

- `MarkerSighting`: `track_id, marker_id, distance, lateral_offset, bearing_angle, confidence, first_seen_t, last_seen_t`
- `VehicleState`: `speed, yaw, yaw_rate, is_lane_visible, steering_confidence` — sourced from IMU + `AIDriver` + lane detector, read-only input to missions.
- `MissionCommand`: `throttle, steering, nav_state_label, debug_annotations` — the only thing a `Mission` is allowed to produce each frame.
- `MissionOutcome`: `SUCCESS | ABORTED | FAILED` — reported once, at completion, from `Mission` to `MissionManager`.

No module reaches into another module's internal state. This is what allows dozens of mission types to be added without cross-file coupling.

---

## 2. Mission Manager

The `MissionManager` is the single arbiter. Exactly one mission is ever "active." Its responsibilities:

- **Active mission**: holds at most one `Mission` instance. While active, the `MissionManager` forwards `update()` calls to it each frame and reads back a `MissionCommand`.
- **Pending candidates**: when `MarkerTracker` reports a *new* confirmed sighting, the manager builds a `MissionCandidate` (marker_id + sighting + timestamp) and holds it in a small pending queue rather than activating immediately — activation still requires validation (below).
- **Validation before activation**, in order:
  1. Marker ID exists in `MarkerRegistry` → otherwise ignored (unknown/invalid marker).
  2. `required_vehicle_state` matches current `VehicleState` (e.g. must be in `LANE_FOLLOWING`, must have `is_lane_visible=True`).
  3. `required_mission_state` matches current manager state (e.g. "no other mission active," or "must follow mission X").
  4. Cooldown for this `marker_id` has elapsed (per-marker cooldown ledger, keyed by `marker_id`, not by track — repeated sightings of the same physical marker within the cooldown window are ignored).
  5. If `one_time = True`, marker_id is not in the completed-missions history.
  6. `SafetyMonitor.permits_activation()` returns true.
  7. Priority check (below).
- **Priority & interruption**: every `MissionDefinition` carries an integer `priority`. A pending candidate with strictly higher priority than the active mission may **interrupt** it; the active mission is given a chance to `on_interrupt()` (most missions will treat this as "abort safely," see §4) before the new one activates. Equal-or-lower priority candidates are discarded (not queued for later — a missed lower-priority marker is simply not executed, which is the correct, deterministic behaviour for a single-vehicle system with no "unfinished business" backlog).
- **Completed missions**: on `MissionOutcome.SUCCESS`, the manager records `(marker_id, timestamp)` in a completion history — this is what backs `one_time` markers. `FAILED`/`ABORTED` outcomes are recorded separately for diagnostics but do **not** count against `one_time`, so a marker whose mission failed can be retried on the next approach.
- **Cooldown ledger**: independent of completion history. Applies to *every* activation attempt (including repeatable missions), preventing the same marker from re-triggering every frame while the vehicle is physically sitting near it.
- **Mission cancellation**: the manager cancels the active mission (calls `on_abort()`) when: the `SafetyMonitor` demands it, the mission's own internal watchdog expires (`Mission` reports `is_stuck()`), or an operator pause/resume is issued from `main_auto.py`. After cancellation, control always returns to `LANE_FOLLOWING` — never to an undefined state.

The `MissionManager` never contains marker-specific logic. It only ever calls generic methods on `Mission` instances and generic lookups on `MarkerRegistry`.

---

## 3. Marker Registry Design

The registry is a flat, declarative mapping — conceptually a table, not code:

| Field | Type | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| `marker_id` | int | ArUco dictionary ID |
| `mission_type` | string | Key into `MissionFactory` (e.g. `"intersection_branch"`, `"stop"`, `"ignore"`) |
| `trigger_distance` | float (m) | Distance at which the candidate becomes eligible for `PENDING` |
| `trigger_direction` | enum {`APPROACH`, `DEPARTURE`, `EITHER`} | Whether the marker should fire while approaching, while leaving, or either — derived from the sign of the closing rate computed by `MarkerTracker` |
| `cooldown_s` | float | Minimum time between activation attempts for this marker_id |
| `priority` | int | Higher wins on interruption |
| `activation_rules` | list of predicate references | Composable conditions (e.g. `min_confidence(0.6)`, `lateral_offset_within(±0.3m)`) evaluated by the manager before activation |
| `required_vehicle_state` | enum/set | e.g. `{LANE_FOLLOWING}` |
| `required_mission_state` | enum/set | e.g. `{NONE}` (no active mission) or a specific predecessor mission |
| `repeatable` | bool | If false, only the first successful execution counts (see one-time semantics above) |
| `safety_conditions` | list of predicate references | Extra checks specific to this marker (e.g. "only if speed < 0.5") |
| `recovery_behaviour` | enum | `RETURN_TO_LANE_CENTER`, `HOLD_POSITION`, `RESUME_LAST_MISSION` — passed into the mission's `RECOVER` phase |
| `params` | free-form dict | Mission-specific configuration (e.g. for `intersection_branch`: `branch_probability=0.5`, `turn_radius`, `side_road_marker_offset`) |

This table is the **only** place marker behaviour is defined. It is described fully in §9 (Configuration Design). Extending the system to a new marker is: add a row. Extending the system to a new *kind* of behaviour is: add one `Mission` subclass and one `MissionFactory` registration — the registry table format itself never changes.

---

## 4. Mission Lifecycle

Every mission — regardless of type — passes through the same generic lifecycle, driven by the `MissionManager` and implemented by lightweight hooks on the `Mission` base class. This is what prevents "a new if/else block per marker."

```
Marker Detected (MarkerTracker confirms sighting)
        |
        v
Validation  (MissionManager: registry lookup, cooldown, one-time,
             required states, safety monitor permit, priority)
        |  (any failure -> candidate discarded, no state change)
        v
Mission Selection  (MissionFactory.create(mission_type, definition, sighting))
        |
        v
Mission Activation  (MissionManager sets active mission; Navigator state
                     transitions LANE_FOLLOWING -> MISSION_PENDING)
        |
        v
+------------------------ Mission Execution -----------------------+
|  PENDING   -> mission confirms trigger conditions are still true  |
|  APPROACH  -> vehicle continues toward marker under lane-following|
|              blended with mission-specific speed scaling          |
|  PREPARE   -> mission commits to a trajectory decision (this is   |
|              where Random Route Selection happens, exactly once)  |
|  EXECUTE   -> mission drives the maneuver (open-loop timed/yaw-   |
|              target primitives, or closed-loop blended steering)  |
|  RECOVER   -> mission blends its own control authority back down  |
|              to zero while AIDriver's lane steering blends up     |
+---------------------------------------------------------------------+
        |
        v
Completion  (Mission reports MissionOutcome; MissionManager updates
             cooldown ledger + completion history)
        |
        v
Return to Lane Following  (Navigator state MISSION_RECOVER -> LANE_FOLLOWING;
                           MissionManager.active_mission = None)
```

Each phase transition inside "Mission Execution" is driven by the mission instance itself (`Mission.should_advance_phase()`), not by the manager — the manager only knows "a mission is running" and "here is its last reported command," keeping it mission-type-agnostic.

---

## 5. Random Route Selection Strategy

Random selection is deliberately **not** a manager-level concern — it is encapsulated entirely inside the mission instance that needs it (e.g. `IntersectionBranchMission`), via a small injectable `RouteDecisionStrategy` interface. This keeps the `MissionManager` fully generic and lets future missions use non-random decision strategies (e.g. rule-based, or externally commanded) without touching the manager.

Guarantees required by the spec, and how each is met structurally:

- **Randomly selects between available routes**: `RandomRouteStrategy.choose(options, weights)` — for the first mission, `options = [CONTINUE_MAIN, ENTER_SIDE_ROAD]` with `branch_probability` from `params` (default 0.5/0.5), drawn from a seeded RNG owned by the `Mission` instance (not a global RNG), so runs are reproducible in test/replay mode if the seed is fixed.
- **Guarantees only one selection**: the decision is made exactly once, at the **moment the mission transitions `PENDING -> PREPARE`**, and is cached as an instance attribute (`self.chosen_route`) on the `Mission` object for the remainder of its lifecycle. Because `PREPARE` is only entered once per mission instance (enforced by the phase state machine itself, not by re-checking a condition), the RNG is never called twice for the same physical marker encounter.
- **Prevents repeated decisions**: because the decision is mission-instance state, not global or config state, a second encounter with the *same* marker (a new `Mission` instance, created after cooldown/one-time rules permit it) is free to draw a new independent random outcome — this is correct behaviour, not a bug, since "repeated decisions across separate encounters" is desired variety, while "repeated decisions within one encounter" is the thing being prevented.
- **Survives temporary marker loss**: because the choice is cached at `PREPARE` entry and the `EXECUTE`/`RECOVER` phases that follow do not depend on continued marker visibility (they run as an open-loop timed/yaw-target maneuver — see §6), losing sight of the marker mid-turn (which will always happen, since the marker is behind or beside the vehicle once it starts turning) has no effect on the outcome. `MarkerTracker`'s debounced "lost" signal is only consulted by the `SafetyMonitor` for timeout/watchdog purposes, never to re-trigger the decision.

---

## 6. Navigation Strategy

The turning strategy is deliberately **not hardcoded per marker**. Instead, `Mission.EXECUTE` phases are built from a small library of reusable, parameterized **maneuver primitives**, selected and configured via `params` in the registry, not via new code per marker:

- **`TimedStraightAdvance(duration_s, speed_scale)`** — used for `APPROACH`/pre-turn straight segments (replaces the old hardcoded `PRE_TURN_ADVANCE` constant with a per-mission parameter).
- **`YawTargetTurn(target_yaw_delta_deg, speed_scale, max_duration_s)`** — closed-loop on IMU yaw (already available via `imu_reader.py`/`current_yaw`), used for the actual branch turn. Watchdog-bounded by `max_duration_s`.
- **`BlendedLaneReturn(blend_duration_s)`** — ramps mission steering authority down to 0% and `AIDriver` lane-following authority up to 100% over a short window, instead of an abrupt handoff. This is the generic `RECOVER` implementation shared by *every* mission type that ends by rejoining a lane.

Handling the specific concerns requested:

- **Approaching the intersection correctly**: `APPROACH` phase runs `AIDriver` lane-following unmodified, with only a speed-scale multiplier from the mission's `params` (mirrors today's `APPROACH_SPEED_SCALE` in `NavConfig`, but now per-mission instead of global).
- **Preparing for turning**: `PREPARE` phase is where the `RouteDecisionStrategy` fires (§5) and, if the outcome is "enter side road," where the mission composes its maneuver primitive sequence (e.g. `[TimedStraightAdvance, YawTargetTurn, BlendedLaneReturn]`) from `params`. If the outcome is "continue main road," the mission composes a trivial sequence (`[]`) and completes immediately, handing control straight back to lane following — this is the natural implementation of "Option A: continue following the main road."
- **Executing the turn**: `EXECUTE` runs the composed primitive sequence in order, each primitive reporting its own completion condition (elapsed time or yaw error under threshold).
- **Recovering into lane following**: `BlendedLaneReturn`, as above — always the last primitive, always shared code, never marker-specific.
- **Handling poor steering predictions**: during `APPROACH` and `RECOVER` (the only phases where `AIDriver` has authority), the `SafetyMonitor` watches `VehicleState.steering_confidence` / raw-vs-smoothed steering delta (reusing the existing smoothing signal in `AIDriver`) and can force an early `RECOVER->ABORT` if steering output is erratic.
- **Handling temporary lane loss**: during `EXECUTE`, the vehicle is deliberately *not* relying on lane detection (it's off the marked lane by design during a branch turn) — this is why `YawTargetTurn` is IMU-driven, not vision-driven. Lane loss only matters again once `RECOVER` starts blending `AIDriver` back in; if lane is still not visible when `RECOVER`'s blend window ends, the `SafetyMonitor` extends a bounded grace period, and if lane is still not found, escalates to abort/stop rather than driving blind.
- **Aborting safely**: every `Mission` implements `on_abort()`, which must always be a safe, bounded action — for maneuvers already committed to a turn, "abort" means "finish the shortest safe path back to a lane" (e.g. skip straight to `BlendedLaneReturn`) rather than a raw motor stop mid-turn, unless the `SafetyMonitor` has independently issued a hard emergency stop (§8), which always overrides at the actuation level regardless of what the mission wants to do.

---

## 7. Navigation State Machine

Two state machines exist at different granularities, intentionally kept separate so mission-internal complexity never leaks into the top-level `Navigator`:

**A. Top-level `NavState`** (owned by `Navigator`, exposed to `main_auto.py`/HUD exactly as today):

```
IDLE
  | start()
  v
LANE_FOLLOWING <----------------------------------------+
  | MissionManager activates a mission                  |
  v                                                      |
MISSION_ACTIVE  (single umbrella state; the mission's    |
  |              internal phase -- PENDING/APPROACH/     |
  |              PREPARE/EXECUTE/RECOVER -- is exposed    |
  |              as a sub-label for telemetry only,      |
  |              e.g. "MISSION_ACTIVE:EXECUTE")           |
  |                                                       |
  +- mission completes normally --------------------------+
  +- mission aborted (safety or watchdog) -----------------+
  |
PAUSED  (operator SPACE, as today) -- reachable from any state, returns
  |      to LANE_FOLLOWING on resume (mission is aborted on pause)
  v
EMERGENCY_STOP  (SafetyMonitor hard trip) -- reachable from any state,
                requires operator resume; motors forced to zero
                regardless of any mission or lane-following output
```

Collapsing all mission execution into one `MISSION_ACTIVE` top-level state (rather than exposing `MISSION_PENDING/PREPARE/EXECUTE/RECOVER` as top-level states, as the prompt's example sketch suggested) is a deliberate simplification: the *sub-phase* is mission-internal and mission-type-specific in duration/meaning, so hoisting it to the top level would force `Navigator` to understand mission internals — exactly the coupling this redesign is meant to remove. `Navigator` only needs to know "lane following," "a mission owns control," "paused," or "stopped." Telemetry/debugging still gets full phase visibility via the `debug_annotations` field on `MissionCommand`.

**B. Mission-internal phase state machine** (owned by each `Mission` instance, per §4/§6): `PENDING -> APPROACH -> PREPARE -> EXECUTE -> RECOVER -> {COMPLETE | ABORTED}`. This is generic across all mission types; individual mission classes only supply the behaviour *within* each phase, not new phases.

---

## 8. Safety

Safety is cross-cutting and evaluated by `SafetyMonitor` every frame, independent of and prioritized above the Mission Manager and any active mission.

- **Missions are rejected (never activated)** when: marker unknown to registry; required vehicle/mission state not met; cooldown active; one-time mission already completed; a higher-or-equal priority mission is already active; `SafetyMonitor.permits_activation()` is false (e.g. current speed exceeds a safe activation threshold, IMU data stale/missing, lane not currently visible for missions that require an `APPROACH` on visible lane).
- **Missions are cancelled mid-execution** when: the mission's own watchdog (`max_duration_s` on its current primitive, or a per-mission overall timeout mirrored from today's `WATCHDOG_TIMEOUT`) expires; `SafetyMonitor` detects an unsafe condition (steering saturation, lane not reacquired within grace period after `RECOVER`, IMU/camera dropout); the operator pauses via `main_auto.py`.
- **Emergency stop** occurs when: `SafetyMonitor` detects a condition it judges unrecoverable by a graceful abort (e.g. sensor dropout during an active `EXECUTE` phase where the vehicle is IMU-blind mid-turn, or a mission watchdog expiring *while already in a cancelled/aborting state* — a double failure). Emergency stop always sets throttle/steering to zero at the `Navigator` output stage, bypassing both `AIDriver` and any mission output — this is a hard override, not a request the mission can veto.
- **Lane following always takes priority** whenever no mission is active or validated — this is structural, not a rule to remember: `MissionManager.active_mission is None` simply means `Navigator` calls `AIDriver` directly, every frame, by default. There is no state where "nothing is driving."
- **Invalid markers** (unknown ID, corrupt pose estimate, `distance` computation failure from `solvePnP`) are filtered at `MarkerTracker`, before they ever reach the registry lookup — they never become `MissionCandidate`s.
- **Duplicate detections** are collapsed by `MarkerTracker`'s `track_id` assignment (a marker seen in consecutive frames is one sighting, not N), and further guarded by the per-marker cooldown ledger in `MissionManager` (so even if a marker is briefly lost and re-acquired, it cannot be re-triggered until cooldown elapses).

---

## 9. Configuration Design

All marker behaviour lives in one declarative configuration source — conceptually a table of `MissionDefinition` rows (§3), intended to be expressed as structured data (e.g. YAML or a Python data-registry module of plain dataclasses) rather than as branching code. Two properties are required of this design, independent of the exact file format chosen at implementation time:

- **No navigation logic file needs to change to add or modify a marker.** Only the configuration source and, if a genuinely new behaviour is needed, a new `Mission` subclass registered with `MissionFactory` — never an edit to `MissionManager`, `Navigator`, or `MarkerTracker`.
- **Validity is checked at load time, not at runtime-per-frame.** On startup, every `mission_type` string in the config is verified against `MissionFactory`'s registered types, every `recovery_behaviour`/`trigger_direction`/`required_vehicle_state` value is verified against its enum, and duplicate `marker_id` entries are rejected — surfacing configuration errors immediately rather than as a silent no-op mission on track day.

The existing scattered constants in `NavConfig`/`ArUcoConfig` (`TRIGGER_DISTANCE`, `STOP_DURATION`, `PRE_TURN_ADVANCE`, `MANEUVER_STRAIGHT`, `APPROACH_SPEED_SCALE`, `MANEUVER_SPEED_SCALE`, `DIST_TRIGGER_DIAGONAL`) should be migrated into this format as the **default `params`** for the relevant built-in mission types, preserving today's tuned values as sensible defaults rather than discarding them.

---

## 10. Future Extensibility

Because every mission type is a `Mission` subclass registered by string key, and every marker's behaviour is a data row rather than code, the following all require **zero changes** to `MarkerRegistry`, `MissionManager`, `Navigator`, `MarkerTracker`, or `SafetyMonitor` — only a new `Mission` subclass (or reuse of an existing one) plus registry rows:

Parking, Charging Station, City Center entry, Warehouse zones, Roundabout, Traffic Lights, Pedestrian Crossing, Delivery Point, fully Custom missions.

**Obstacle Avoidance is explicitly called out as a special case.** This architecture reserves a clean extension point for it (a `mission_type` such as `"obstacle_avoidance"` triggered not by a marker but potentially by a future perception signal, following the exact same `Mission` lifecycle and maneuver-primitive pattern used here). However, per the separate feasibility analysis already performed on this codebase, obstacle avoidance is **not implementable today** regardless of this architecture, because the required perception (obstacle detection) and training data (avoidance/stop-and-wait trajectories) do not exist in the project. This document does not resolve that gap — it only ensures that *if* that gap is closed in the future, integrating the resulting behaviour into the Mission System will not require re-architecting the Mission System itself.

